(The original, lost, was carried out in New â¦MusÃ©e National d'Art Moderne, Centre Georges Pompidou, Paris Julian Wasser Marcel Duchamp, Duchamp Retrospective, Pasadena Art â¦Robert Berman Gallery When the pictures were made, Babitz was a 20-year-old student at Los Angeles Community College. The daughter of a violinist and an artist, and the goddaughter of Russian composer Igor Stravinsky, Babitz was already at ease in a sophisticated, aesthetic milieu. She integrated herself into L.A.âs slowly burgeoning art scene, partying with Billy Al Bengston, Ed Kienholz, Kenneth Price, and the men whoâd become integral to the California Light and Space movement: Larry Bell, Robert Irwin, and Peter Alexander. Years later, she also became romantically involved with both Ed Ruscha and his brother. Babitz fully embraced her role as an art groupie. He founded Los Angelesâs first major gallery, Ferus, in 1957, then left to become a curator at the Pasadena Art Museumânow the Norton Simon Museum. He decided to mount Duchampâs first American retrospective, and include over 100 artworks. At the time, Duchamp had long been out of the public eye. He had gained fame in the 1910s for his concept of the âreadymadeââfound objects such as a bicycle wheel or snow shovel presented as art. Yet in 1923, he proclaimed that he was abandoning artmaking in order to play chess. Two decades later, he began work in secret on an enigmatic masterpiece, Ãtant DonnÃ©s (1946â66). When the show ran, he wasâat least publiclyâa retired artist in his mid-seventies. Babitz claims that she didnât receive an invite to the exhibitionâs opening part at the Hotel Green because Hoppsâs wife was in town, but even Babitzâs 17-year-old sister, Mirandi, got to attendâand photographer Julian Wasser drove her to the fÃªte. Seething with envy, Babitz wanted to take revenge on her paramour. Wasser, who was known for taking nude photographs of young female Angelenos, suggested a titillating form of retribution: playing chess at the museum, in the buff, with Duchamp. Julian Wasser Duchamp with Walter Hopps, Duchamp Retrospective, Pasadena Art Museum, 1963Robert Berman Gallery Babitz told the Archives of American Art that the proposition seemed âlike the best idea Iâd ever heard in my life.â¦I mean, it was, not only was it vengeance, it was art.â Lessening her own inhibitions, perhaps, was the fact that Wasser had already shot her naked, at her own command: In the pre-iPhone era, sheâd requested and received sexy snapshots to share with men. Wasser coordinated the photo shoot without alerting either the museum or Duchamp about his intentions. Babitzâs performance took place before the museum opened, so her audience was the teamster staff âmarching back and forth with big pieces of art,â as she once explained. During the game, Babitz and Duchamp discussed her godfather, Stravinsky, and his famous 1910 suite, The Firebird. Duchamp won their games as Wasser clicked his shutter. Eventually, Hopps walked into the gallery and was so surprised that his Double Mint gum fell out of his mouth. According to Babitz, he began returning her calls after the incident. Julian Wasser Duchamp making a chess move in distance, Duchamp Retrospective, Pasadena Art Museum,, 1963Robert Berman Gallery Wasser showed Babitz the proofs, and she ultimately selected one in which she was turned away from the camera, her face obscured by her bobbed hair. The choice, as Lili Anolik points out in her Babitz biography, Hollywoodâs Eve (2019), gives the picture additional strangeness as it simultaneously depicts shyness and exhibitionism, a plea for both attention and anonymity. Anolik writes that Babitz âwasnât just model and muse, passive and pliable, but artist and instigator, wicked and subversive.â As Babitz told her biographer, âWalter thought he was running the show, and I finally got to run something.âThroughout the following decades, she published seven books. Both her fiction and non-fiction glistened with memoristic detail about her Hollywood surroundings, passionate love affairs, and colorful friends. Without help from Wasserâs framing or Duchampâs fame, Babitz harnessed the power of her sexuality and fearlessness into art that was all her own.
